    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The origin of magnetic fields in galaxies is currently barely constrained. Current techniques to find magnetic fields in high redshift galaxies (detection of continuum emission, or Faraday rotation against a background quasar) cease to be useful around z~2. To go to higher redshifts, new techniques are required. ALMA's newly-commissioned polarization capability provides just such a new method by expoliting the alignment of dust grains with the large-scale magnetic field. Such an alignment leads to a small net polarization of the far-infrared emission, which is detectable in the brightest submm galaxies with ALMA even in Early Science operations, and, furthermore, may be enhanced by the strong outflows expected in such systems. We are therefore targeting the hyperluminous starburst/quasar pair BR 1202-0725, which has already been well-studied in ALMA Science Verification. Both objects in this unique system are bright enough to detect a polarized signal if they have large-scale magnetic fields. Having such a pair also allows us to investigate whether the presence of an AGN may be important for providing a seed field, besides giving us a check against systematic error.</prp:abstract>
